Module 2, Lesson 1: readr

In this first lesson of Module 2, you were introduced to the tidyverse, a package of packages that provides you with all of the tools for translating your data into useful information and knowledge. One of the packages that comprises the tidyverse is readr, which contains tools for reading data into R.

In Module 1, Lesson 2, you created an R project called GlobalFindex.Rproj and, in that same folder, you created a script called IndicatorTable.R. We will be working inside that script now. Double click the GlobalFindex.Rproj file to open a new RStudio session. Then, open the IndicatorTable.R script. The easiest way to do so is to inspect the file tree in the bottom-right panel of your RStudio session and look for the file name (it will be there if you were able to successfully follow the instructions to create this script in Module 1). Click the file name:

Image description: opening an existing script from the bottom-right file panel

If you haven’t yet done so, put this code (that is, library(tidyverse)) on the first line of your IndicatorTable.R script and then run it by simultaneously pressing ‘Cmd+Enter’ (on your Mac) or ‘Ctrl+Enter’ (on your Windows computer).

## ── Attaching packages ─────────────────────────────────────── tidyverse 1.3.2 ──
## ✔ ggplot2 3.3.6     ✔ purrr   0.3.4
## ✔ tibble  3.1.7     ✔ dplyr   1.0.9
## ✔ tidyr   1.2.0     ✔ stringr 1.4.0
## ✔ readr   2.1.2     ✔ forcats 0.5.1
## ── Conflicts ────────────────────────────────────────── tidyverse_conflicts() ──
## ✖ dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
## ✖ dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()

If by chance you haven’t created the IndicatorTable.R script, you can do so now: press ‘Cmd+Shift+N’ (on your Mac) or ‘Ctrl+Shift+N’ (on your Windows computer) to create a new script. Then, put the library command from above on the very first line, then save the script by pressing ‘Cmd+S’ or ‘Ctrl+S’, choosing IndicatorTable.R as the file name.

read_csv()

The function from the readr that we’ll practice using here is the read_csv function, which takes a computer file is saved as a comma-separated value (csv) format on your computer and reads it into your R session.

Look for the .csv suffix on a computer file (ironically, if you double click that file to open it, most computers will use their spreadsheet software program, e.g. Excel, to view it, and you won’t even see the commas that separate the values!).

To get the Global Findex data onto your computer, go to this url:

https://microdata.worldbank.org/index.php/catalog/3324/get-microdata

If you haven’t already done so, you will need to register for a free account before you can access the data. After logging in, download the data in CSV format. The ZIP file will be named WLD_2017_FINDEX_v02_M_CSV.zip, and when you unzip it the resulting folder will contain a single file named micro_world.csv, which is the data we need.

If you are working on RStudio installed on your own computer, move this micro_world.csv file into the GlobalFindex project folder, e.g. by dragging and dropping. If you go back to RStudio now, the bottom-right of your RStudio session should indicate that the micro_world.csv file is now in your directory:

Image description: the GlobalFindex project after moving the data to the folder

If you are working on RStudio from rstudio.cloud, you will need to upload the micro_world.csv data into your project. To do so, in the files panel, look for the ‘Upload’ button, which is unique to rstudio.cloud.

Image description: uploading the micro_world.csv into rstudio.cloud

Now we are ready to read in the data. In your IndicatorTable.R script, type the following line of code, which will read in the Global Findex data stored in the file named micro_world.csv and assign it as an object in your R session entitled micro_world:

micro_world <- read_csv("micro_world.csv")
## Rows: 154923 Columns: 105
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: ","
## chr   (3): economy, economycode, regionwb
## dbl (102): pop_adult, wpid_random, wgt, female, age, educ, inc_q, emp_in, fi...
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.

Remember, typing the line of code in your script doesn’t run the code; at this point it is only a set of instructions to be run. Tell R to run the code by pressing ‘Cmd+Enter’ (Mac) or ‘Ctrl+Enter’ (Windows). If successfully run, you should see output in your console similar to what you see above: some information about the numbers of rows and columns in your data and the variable (column) names. If you get an error that says Error: object 'read_csv' not found, it is likely because you did not first load the tidyverse, which contains the read_csv function.

The last thing to do is save your work. Because you’ve made changes, the file name looks like IndicatorTable.R*. Save your script by pressing ‘Cmd+S’ or ‘Ctrl+S’, and the file name once again becomes IndicatorTable.R.
